LOGIN SERVICE — CODE EXPLANATION
=================================
A plain-English walkthrough of every file in the project.


═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
1. pom.xml  (project blueprint)
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

This is Maven's configuration file. Think of it as a shopping
list that tells Maven which libraries to download before
compiling the project.

We only pull in 4 dependencies:

  spring-boot-starter-web
    Gives us an embedded Tomcat server and the ability to handle
    HTTP requests (GET, POST, etc.). Without this, the app
    wouldn't listen on port 8080 at all.

  spring-boot-starter-thymeleaf
    Thymeleaf is a templating engine. It takes our HTML files
    and fills in dynamic values (like the logged-in username)
    before sending the page to the browser.

  spring-boot-starter-security
    Provides the entire login/logout mechanism out of the box —
    session management, CSRF protection, password hashing, and
    the redirect rules. We configure it in SecurityConfig.java.

  spring-boot-starter-actuator
    Adds a /actuator/health endpoint. Azure Spring Apps pings
    this URL to check whether the app is alive and ready to
    receive traffic (called a "readiness probe").

The <parent> block at the top pulls in Spring Boot's default
settings so we don't have to manage library versions manually.


═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
2. LoginServiceApplication.java  (entry point)
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

This is the first file Java executes when the app starts.

  @SpringBootApplication
    A shorthand annotation that tells Spring Boot to:
    - Scan the package for components (controllers, configs, etc.)
    - Auto-configure libraries based on what's on the classpath
    - Start the embedded Tomcat server

  SpringApplication.run(...)
    Boots everything up. After this line the server is live and
    waiting for requests.

That's all this file does. All real logic lives elsewhere.


