3. SecurityConfig.java  (the bouncer)
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

This is where we tell Spring Security how to protect the app.
It has three @Bean methods, each producing one reusable object.

---
userDetailsService(PasswordEncoder encoder)
---
  Creates two hardcoded demo users using Spring's in-memory
  user store. In a real app this would query a database.

  alice  → password: password123  → role: USER
  admin  → password: admin123     → role: ADMIN

  The passwords are NOT stored as plain text. We pass them
  through encoder.encode(...) which produces a BCrypt hash
  (a one-way scramble). When the user logs in, Spring hashes
  the typed password and compares the hashes, never the
  plain text.

---
passwordEncoder()
---
  Returns a BCryptPasswordEncoder instance. BCrypt is the
  industry-standard algorithm for storing passwords safely.
  Spring Security uses this bean automatically.

---
securityFilterChain(HttpSecurity http)
---
  Defines the URL access rules and login/logout behaviour:

  .requestMatchers("/css/**", "/actuator/health", "/login").permitAll()
    These three URL patterns are public — no login needed.
    - /css/**        → stylesheet must load even before login
    - /actuator/health → Azure's health probe must work anytime
    - /login         → obviously the login page must be public

  .anyRequest().authenticated()
    Every other URL (/dashboard, anything else) requires the
    user to be logged in. If not, Spring redirects to /login.

  .formLogin(...)
    - loginPage("/login")         → use our custom HTML page
    - defaultSuccessUrl("/dashboard") → go here on success
    - failureUrl("/login?error")  → go here on bad credentials

  .logout(...)
    - logoutSuccessUrl("/login?logout") → go here after logout
    Spring automatically handles POST /logout and destroys
    the session. We don't write any logout code ourselves.


