4. PageController.java  (the page router)
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

This controller handles two GET requests and returns the name
of the HTML template to render.

---
GET /login  →  loginPage()
---
  Returns the string "login", which Thymeleaf maps to the file
  templates/login.html. Spring Security automatically intercepts
  the POST /login form submission — we don't write that handler.

---
GET /dashboard  →  dashboard(Authentication, Model)
---
  Spring Security injects an Authentication object into this
  method automatically. It contains everything about the
  currently logged-in user.

  We extract two things and put them in the Model:
    username  → the user's login name (e.g. "alice")
    roles     → their granted authorities (e.g. [ROLE_USER])

  Thymeleaf reads these from the Model and inserts them into
  the dashboard HTML using th:text="${username}".

  If someone tries to access /dashboard without being logged in,
  Spring Security intercepts the request before this method even
  runs and redirects to /login.


