5. application.properties  (runtime settings)
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

  spring.application.name=login-service
    Names the app. Azure Spring Apps uses this name in logs and
    in the default URL it generates.

  server.port=8080
    The port Tomcat listens on. Azure Spring Apps expects 8080
    by default.

  management.endpoints.web.exposure.include=health
    Only expose the /actuator/health endpoint over HTTP. Keeps
    all other actuator endpoints (metrics, env, etc.) private.

  management.endpoint.health.show-details=always
    Makes the health response include component details like
    disk space and ping status. Useful for debugging.


═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
6. login.html  (the login form)
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

A Thymeleaf HTML template. Lines starting with "th:" are
Thymeleaf attributes that are processed server-side.

  th:action="@{/login}"
    Generates the correct form action URL including any
    context path. Spring Security listens on POST /login.

  name="username" and name="password"
    These field names are what Spring Security looks for. They
    must be exactly "username" and "password" (or you'd need
    extra config).

  th:if="${param.error}"
    Shows a red error banner only when the URL contains ?error
    (which Spring Security adds after a failed login attempt).

  th:if="${param.logout}"
    Shows a green success banner only when the URL contains
    ?logout (which Spring Security adds after logout).

  The CSRF token is injected automatically by Thymeleaf's
  Spring Security integration. Without it, Spring would reject
  the POST as a potential cross-site request forgery attack.


═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
7. dashboard.html  (the post-login page)
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

  th:text="${username}"
    Replaced at render time with the value "alice" or "admin"
    that PageController put in the Model.

  th:text="${roles}"
    Replaced with the user's roles, e.g. [ROLE_USER].

  th:action="@{/logout}"
    The logout form POSTs to /logout. Thymeleaf automatically
    includes the CSRF token so Spring Security accepts it.

  Why POST for logout? Using GET /logout would allow an
  attacker to embed an image tag like:
    <img src="https://yourapp.com/logout">
  ...and silently log users out. POST + CSRF token prevents this.


