9. .github/workflows/deploy.yml  (the CI/CD pipeline)
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

This file tells GitHub Actions what to do automatically every
time you push code to the main branch.

---
Trigger
---
  on:
    push:
      branches: [main]

  The pipeline runs on every push to main. It does NOT run on
  other branches, so you can work on feature branches freely.

---
Job 1: build
---
  Runs on a fresh Ubuntu virtual machine provided by GitHub.

  Step 1 — Checkout source code
    Downloads the repository contents onto the VM.

  Step 2 — Set up Java 17
    Installs Java 17 (Temurin distribution) and enables the
    Maven dependency cache. Caching ~/.m2 speeds up subsequent
    runs by reusing already-downloaded libraries.

  Step 3 — Build with Maven
    mvn clean package -DskipTests
    - clean    → delete any previous build output
    - package  → compile and package everything into a JAR file
    - -DskipTests → skip unit tests for demo speed

  Step 4 — Upload JAR
    Saves the built JAR file as a GitHub Actions artifact so
    the next job (deploy) can download it.

---
Job 2: deploy
---
  Only runs if Job 1 (build) succeeded.

  Step 1 — Download JAR
    Retrieves the JAR that build job uploaded.

  Step 2 — Log in to Azure
    Uses the AZURE_CREDENTIALS secret (a service principal JSON)
    to authenticate with Azure. This is like logging in with
    "az login" but non-interactively.

  Step 3 — Deploy to Azure Spring Apps
    Uses Microsoft's official azure/spring-apps-deploy action.
    It uploads the JAR to your Azure Spring Apps instance and
    triggers a rolling deployment. Azure handles starting the
    new version and stopping the old one.

---
Secrets vs Variables
---
  Secrets (AZURE_CREDENTIALS, AZURE_SUBSCRIPTION_ID)
    Encrypted values. Never shown in logs. Used for sensitive
    auth material.

  Variables (AZURE_RESOURCE_GROUP, AZURE_SPRING_APPS_NAME,
              SPRING_APP_NAME)
    Plain text values. Visible in logs. Used for non-sensitive
    config that might differ between environments.


═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
HOW A LOGIN FLOWS END TO END
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

1. User visits https://your-app.azuremicroservices.io/dashboard

2. Spring Security checks: is there a valid session for this
   request? No → redirect to /login.

3. Browser loads GET /login → PageController.loginPage() runs
   → Thymeleaf renders login.html and sends it to the browser.

4. User types "alice" and "password123", clicks Sign in.

5. Browser sends POST /login with the form data.

6. Spring Security intercepts this POST (our code never sees it).
   It looks up "alice" in the UserDetailsService, BCrypt-hashes
   "password123", and compares it to the stored hash.

7. Match! Spring Security creates a session, stores it in a
   cookie, and redirects the browser to /dashboard.

8. Browser follows redirect to GET /dashboard.

9. Spring Security checks the session cookie — valid. Allows
   the request through.

10. PageController.dashboard() runs, adds "alice" and
    "[ROLE_USER]" to the Model.

11. Thymeleaf renders dashboard.html with those values and
    sends it to the browser.

12. User sees "Signed in as alice".
